# ║  PERF-001/002/003 — Report generation: ~1 hour → ~5 minutes            ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS (240 reports taking ~1 hour):                      ║
# ║    86% of time: LibreOffice spawning a new JVM per DOCX (~10 s each)   ║
# ║    • 240 × 10 s = 40 min just for PDF conversion                        ║
# ║    Remaining 14%: template disk re-read, image re-decode, exiftool      ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  PERF-001 — Template pre-load into bytes (line ~17307):                 ║
# ║    Template DOCX was re-opened from disk on EVERY row via               ║
# ║    Document(template_path). Now read once into _template_bytes and      ║
# ║    each row uses Document(BytesIO(_template_bytes)) — zero disk I/O     ║
# ║    in the loop. Saves ~1.6 min (240 × 0.4 s).                          ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  PERF-002 — Image cache (line ~17352):                                  ║
# ║    _cached_image() wraps get_clean_image(). Identical source images     ║
# ║    are only decoded/resized/JPEG-saved once per batch. Subsequent rows  ║
# ║    referencing the same file get the cached output path instantly.      ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  PERF-003 — Batch PDF conversion via _batch_convert_to_pdf():          ║
# ║    THE MAIN FIX. Instead of calling _convert_to_pdf() per DOCX (each   ║
# ║    spawning a new LibreOffice JVM), all DOCX paths are accumulated in   ║
# ║    _pending_docx and converted in ONE soffice call after the loop.      ║
# ║    LibreOffice JVM starts once, processes all files, exits once.        ║
# ║    Files are chunked at 50 per call to avoid Windows arg-length limits. ║
# ║    Falls back to per-file conversion if the batch call fails.           ║
# ║    Expected time: 40 min → ~1–2 min for 240 PDFs.                      ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  COMBINED IMPACT: ~60 min → ~5 min for 240 reports.                    ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-VERIFY-001 FIX — Verification CSV completely rewritten             ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE:                                                             ║
# ║    _extract_reports_to_csv() dumped raw DOCX table rows as pipe-        ║
# ║    separated strings with columns: DOCX File | Table Index | Row Index  ║
# ║    | Cell Count | Row Data. This was machine-unreadable and useless      ║
# ║    for cross-checking temperatures against the source detection CSV.    ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX — Complete rewrite of _extract_reports_to_csv():                  ║
# ║    • Walks all DOCX tables (including nested) looking for label→value   ║
# ║      2-cell rows, matching labels case-insensitively via LABEL_MAP.     ║
# ║    • Produces ONE row per report with named columns:                    ║
# ║        Component, Created, File_Size_KB,                                ║
# ║        Camera_Model, Lens, Range_Max, Range_Min,                        ║
# ║        Emissivity, Distance, Refl_Temp, Humidity,                       ║
# ║        Sp1, Sp2, Sp3, Sp4, NETA_Status, Hotspot_Found                  ║
# ║    • Uses DictWriter with explicit fieldnames — no more raw pipe rows.  ║
# ║    • Per-file errors are logged but don't abort the whole extraction.   ║
# ║    • Output: annotated/verification_report_{timestamp}.csv              ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-NEGTEMP-001 + BUG-SENTINEL-001 + BUG-UNIT-001                     ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  BUG-NEGTEMP-001  Genuine negative reflected temps were being clamped   ║
# ║    _refl_temp_is_bad() and _sgm_temp() used abs(fv) < 0.5 threshold.   ║
# ║    This incorrectly rejected valid values like -0.3°C. Narrowed to      ║
# ║    abs(fv) < 0.05 — only true K→C float artifacts (e.g. -6.1e-6°C)    ║
# ║    are caught. -6°C, -10°C, -0.3°C etc. now pass through unchanged.    ║
# ║    Lower bound (fv < -40) also removed — extreme cold is valid.         ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  BUG-SENTINEL-001  '-273.15' string not in explicit bad-value set       ║
# ║    _range_is_bad() only had '-273' in the explicit set; '-273.15'       ║
# ║    was caught numerically but generated an unnecessary float parse.     ║
# ║    Added '-273.15' to the explicit string set.                          ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  BUG-UNIT-001  Refl. Temp and Range Max/Min always showed °C in reports ║
# ║    even when TempUnit == 'F'. These fields are stored in °C in the CSV  ║
# ║    and were never converted for display.                                 ║
# ║    FIX: New _fmt_temp(val, unit) helper converts °C→°F at display time. ║
# ║         New _fmt_range(val, unit) does the same for integer range fields.║
# ║    Applied to: both report_data construction paths, cam_data table,     ║
# ║    and param_data (Refl. Temp) table in _populate_template_tables.      ║
# ║    Example: Range Max 120°C → 248°F, Refl. Temp 20°C → 68.00°F.       ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-NEGZERO-001 FIX — "-0.00" display in Refl. Temp field             ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE:                                                             ║
# ║    Python's f"{v:.2f}" formats -0.001 as "-0.00" because the float      ║
# ║    is negative even though it rounds to zero. The sentinel check        ║
# ║    (abs < 0.5) prevented this for the true 0K sentinel but still left   ║
# ║    a window for values like -0.001 that pass the sentinel clamp.        ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX — New _fmt_celsius() helper (line ~1475):                          ║
# ║    • Clamps any value where abs(fv) < 0.005 (rounds to 0.00) → "0.00"  ║
# ║    • All other values format normally — "-6.00", "-10.00", "20.00" etc  ║
# ║    • Genuine temperatures like -6°C, -10°C are completely unaffected    ║
# ║    • Applied to all three Refl. Temp format sites in report generation  ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-FILENAME-001 FIX — Remove "Report_" prefix from DOCX/PDF names    ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX (line ~17682):                                                      ║
# ║    docx_path was f"Report_{stem}.docx" → now f"{stem}.docx"             ║
# ║    PDF is derived from docx_path via _convert_to_pdf(), so it also      ║
# ║    drops the prefix automatically.                                       ║
# ║    CSV files (Report_*.csv) are NOT affected — other pipeline code       ║
# ║    globs for them explicitly with "Report_*.csv" pattern.               ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-REFL-TEMP-002 FIX — Near-zero Kelvin conversion artifact          ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE:                                                             ║
# ║    v3.30.25.12 used `fv == 0.0` to detect the FLIR factory sentinel.    ║
# ║    However the camera sometimes stores a value just below 273.15 K       ║
# ║    (e.g. 273.149 K → -0.001°C after K→C subtraction). This passes the  ║
# ║    exact equality check and formats as "-0.00°C" in reports.            ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX — Both _refl_temp_is_bad() and _sgm_temp():                        ║
# ║    Changed `fv == 0.0` → `abs(fv) < 0.5`                               ║
# ║    Any value within ±0.5°C of zero is treated as the factory sentinel.  ║
# ║    These values will be replaced with the 20.0°C default.               ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-REFL-TEMP-001 FIX — ReflectedApparentTemperature 0.0 sentinel     ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE:                                                             ║
# ║    FLIR cameras store ReflectedApparentTemperature = 0.0°C as their     ║
# ║    factory default when the field has never been user-configured.        ║
# ║    exiftool returns this literally as "0.0", which _sgm() passes        ║
# ║    through unchanged. The value "0.0" is then:                          ║
# ║      • Written to CSV as "0.0" by the scan pipeline                     ║
# ║      • Read back by the report pipeline as "0.0"                        ║
# ║      • Rendered in reports as "0.00°C" (wrong — should be 20.0°C)      ║
# ║    The _needs_flir_fallback check never triggered for this field         ║
# ║    because "0.0" is a valid non-empty, non-N/A string.                  ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX 1 — CSV write path: new _sgm_temp() helper (line ~24825)          ║
# ║    Wraps _sgm() for atmospheric temperature fields. Treats exactly       ║
# ║    0.0 as sentinel → returns default (20.0°C). Also rejects values      ║
# ║    outside the realistic ambient range (-40 to 200°C).                  ║
# ║    Applied to: Reflected_Temp, Atmospheric_Temp CSV columns.            ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX 2 — Report merge: _refl_temp_is_bad() helper (line ~17368)        ║
# ║    Added alongside _range_is_bad(). Detects 0.0, N/A, empty, and       ║
# ║    out-of-range values for ReflectedApparentTemperature. Wired into     ║
# ║    _needs_flir_fallback and the flir_meta merge loop.                   ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX 3 — Final safety clamp (line ~17441)                               ║
# ║    If ReflectedApparentTemperature is still bad after all fallback       ║
# ║    attempts (RJPEG inaccessible, metadata missing), force "20.0".       ║
# ║    Logs a warning for traceability.                                      ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  IMPACT: Reports always show 20.00°C for Refl. Temp when the camera     ║
# ║  has the factory-default 0.0°C stored. Old CSVs with "0.0" are         ║
# ║  repaired at report-generation time via the safety clamp.               ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  BUG-SGM-RANGE-001 COMPLETE FIX — Range Max/Min always show 120/-20    ║
# ║  when FLIR metadata is unavailable                                       ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE (re-diagnosed):                                              ║
# ║    Three compounding problems caused -153 / -293 in reports:            ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║    1. _sgm_range() (CSV write) checked the POST-conversion result to    ║
# ║       decide if input was Kelvin. Celsius inputs (-20, 120) converted   ║
# ║       to -293/-153 by subtraction, then the check fired again →         ║
# ║       wrote corrupted values to CSV. (Fixed in v3.30.25.10)             ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║    2. flir_meta merge at report-time only replaced values in the set    ║
# ║       ('N/A', '', '-273'). Corrupted values '-293'/'-153' were not in   ║
# ║       that set, so they were NOT replaced during the FLIR metadata      ║
# ║       merge, even when a fresh RJPEG fetch was done.                    ║
# ║       FIX: Use _range_is_bad() helper for Range_Min/Max merge check.   ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║    3. When FLIR metadata fetch fails or CameraTemperatureRange keys     ║
# ║       are absent, bad values persisted with no final safety net.        ║
# ║       FIX: Added FINAL SAFETY CLAMP after all fallback/conversion       ║
# ║       logic. If Range_Min is still bad → force '-20'. If Range_Max is  ║
# ║       still bad → force '120'. Logs a warning for traceability.         ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  IMPACT: Range Max always shows 120 and Range Min always shows -20      ║
# ║  in reports when the camera range cannot be reliably determined.        ║
# ║  Eliminates -153 / -293 from all future and retroactive reports.        ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝


# ║  CRITICAL REPORT FALLBACK FIX — Handles Legacy CSV Data                ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  BUG-EXIF-RANGE-009  Widened FLIR fallback to run independently         ║
# ║    CRITICAL FIX: Previous fallback logic (v3.30.25.8) only ran when     ║
# ║    Camera Model was N/A. This left Lens showing N/A even when Camera    ║
# ║    was correctly "FLIR E75". New logic runs fallback for ANY field      ║
# ║    that is N/A or missing, checking each field independently:           ║
# ║      • Model == 'N/A'  → fetch FLIR metadata                            ║
# ║      • LensModel == 'N/A'  → fetch FLIR metadata (INDEPENDENT)          ║
# ║      • Range_Min in ('N/A', '', None, '-273')  → fetch FLIR metadata    ║
# ║      • Range_Max in ('N/A', '', None, '-273')  → fetch FLIR metadata    ║
# ║    Added '-273' to trigger list to catch sentinel values from old CSVs. ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  BUG-EXIF-RANGE-010  Enhanced range value conversion triggers           ║
# ║    Previous check only looked for >200 (Kelvin) but missed -273         ║
# ║    (sentinel for 0K unset camera). New logic checks:                    ║
# ║      • value > 200  → Kelvin, needs conversion                          ║
# ║      • value == -273  → Sentinel, fetch fresh FLIR metadata             ║
# ║      • value < -100  → Unrealistic, fetch fresh FLIR metadata           ║
# ║    This handles CSV data written with old code that has literal "-273"  ║
# ║    strings. Fresh FLIR metadata is fetched and converted K→C.           ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  ROOT CAUSE OF INCONSISTENT REPORTS:                                     ║
# ║    Some reports showed correct values, others showed N/A/-273. This     ║
# ║    happened because:                                                     ║
# ║    1. CSV was generated with OLD code → contains "-273" and "N/A"       ║
# ║    2. Report reads CSV → gets literal string values                     ║
# ║    3. v3.30.25.8 fallback only triggered when Camera==N/A              ║
# ║    4. Lens stayed N/A because Camera was correct ("FLIR E75")           ║
# ║    5. Range stayed -273 because fallback didn't check for -273          ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  FIX BEHAVIOR:                                                           ║
# ║    Reports now ALWAYS fetch fresh FLIR metadata when ANY field is N/A   ║
# ║    or -273, regardless of other field values. Each field is checked     ║
# ║    independently. Range values are re-fetched and converted K→C even    ║
# ║    if CSV contains old sentinel values.                                 ║
# ║                                                                          ║
# ║  IMPACT: Resolves inconsistent report generation where some images      ║
# ║  showed correct Lens/Range values while others showed N/A/-273.         ║
# ║  Works retroactively on old CSV data generated before v3.30.25.8.       ║
# ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

